<H2>Agreement on Document Rendering</H2>
<DIV class=3DblogPost>
<DIV style=3D"CLEAR: both"></DIV>
<P></P>
<DIV=20
style=3D"PADDING-BOTTOM: 0px; MARGIN: 0px; PADDING-LEFT: 0px; =
PADDING-RIGHT: 0px; DISPLAY: inline; PADDING-TOP: 0px"=20
id=3Dscid:0767317B-992E-4b12-91E0-4F059A8CECA8:489b0ace-a84b-43f9-a3e8-b5=
7e48580012=20
class=3DwlWriterSmartContent>Technorati Tags: <A=20
href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/interoperability" =
rel=3Dtag>interoperability</A>,=20
<A href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/document%20formats" =
rel=3Dtag>document=20
formats</A>, <A =
href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/document%20processing"=20
rel=3Dtag>document processing</A>, <A=20
href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/Harmony%20Principles" =
rel=3Dtag>Harmony=20
Principles</A>, <A =
href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/presentation%20conformance"=20
rel=3Dtag>presentation conformance</A>, <A=20
href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/conformance" =
rel=3Dtag>conformance</A>, <A=20
href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/ISO/IEC%2024754" rel=3Dtag>ISO/IEC=20
24754</A></DIV>
<P></P>
<P>One problem for harmonization of document-format implementations in =
the case=20
of ODF and OOXML is the degree to which those specifications may provide =

inadequate specification of how documents are to be presented in order =
for=20
implementations to be adequately interoperable.&nbsp; This situation =
arises=20
between implementations of the same format as well as between different =
document=20
formats.</P>
<P>Along with establishing clarity on how much agreement in presentation =
is=20
required, there is the small matter of being able to somehow confirm =
that an=20
application achieves whatever that level of conformance and =
interoperability=20
is.</P>
<P>As I suggested in "<A=20
href=3D"http://nfoworks.org/diary/2008/08/interoperable-odf-finding-groun=
d-truth.htm">Interoperable=20
ODF: Finding Ground Truth</A>," there are many difficulties to be =
conquered in=20
advancing from the current state of affairs to where there is reliable=20
determination that implementations are substitutable in a particular=20
interoperability setting.&nbsp; </P>
<P>We don't have good ways to even talk about the multiple, interlocking =

problems that lurk beneath the simple desire to have interchange of =
documents in=20
standard formats "just work."</P>
<P>It would be helpful, for starters, to at least have a way to describe =
what a=20
particular document-processing system does in rendering documents that =
it=20
accepts.&nbsp; A checklist on the handling of particular features of an=20
electronic document is also useful in determining conformance and=20
interoperability guidance and, perhaps, eventual mechanical verification =

criteria.</P>
<P>The <A =
href=3D"http://xml.coverpages.org/newsletter/news2008-08-18.html">XML=20
Daily Newslink for 2008-08-18</A> reports on a contribution that may be =
useful=20
in this regard, the "<A=20
href=3D"http://xml.coverpages.org/newsletter/news2008-08-18.html#cite9">F=
irst=20
Edition of ISO/IEC 24754: Minimum Requirements for Specifying Document =
Rendering=20
Systems</A>."&nbsp; From the scope:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>"This International Standard provides an abstract list of the =
features that=20
  a document rendering system may have, thus providing a frame of =
reference,=20
  against which the user and implementor can compare the&nbsp; features =
of a=20
  document rendering system. However, this International Standard does =
not=20
  direct how each document rendering system should behave.</P>
  <P>"This International Standard provides the minimum requirements to =
specify=20
  the features that a document rendering system which transforms =
formatting=20
  objects to rendering output. It may be used as a frame of reference, =
against=20
  which the user, implementer, or software agent may compare the =
features of a=20
  document rendering system.&nbsp; According to these requirements, the =
user may=20
  express what he or she expects of a document rendering system, the =
implementer=20
  may describe the functionality and capability of the document =
rendering system=20
  that he or she implements, and the software agent may negotiate a =
minimum set=20
  of functionality and capability that are shared across different =
document=20
  rendering system implementations."</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The Final Committee Draft (omitting the example in the informative =
appendix)=20
is available as a 7-page, 74 kB <A=20
href=3D"http://www.itscj.ipsj.or.jp/sc34/open/0814.pdf">PDF =
file</A>.&nbsp; </P>
<P>Beside the announcement, here's what attracted my attention:</P>
<UL>
  <LI>The list of features is abstract.&nbsp; The descriptions of how =
individual=20
  feature are handled would normally be in prose, with possible =
reference to=20
  standards applicable to the feature (e.g., font =
substitution).<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20

  <LI>The document assumes an abstract processing model related to that =
for SGML=20
  and XML.&nbsp; The presumption is that rendering is specified =
separately from=20
  logical document format and content.&nbsp; It can, of course, be =
adapted to=20
  the rendering provisions of processors for electronic office documents =
even=20
  though rendering conditions are embedded in the specification for the =
document=20
  format and its elements.&nbsp; So it is definitely minimal and =
something to=20
  start from.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
  <LI>This work was initiated in 2005.&nbsp; The Final Committee Draft =
download=20
  file is dated 2007-10-29; its electronic document was last edited on=20
  2007-01-23.&nbsp; The standard, <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://www.iso.org/iso/search.htm?qt=3D24754&amp;searchSubmit=3DS=
earch&amp;sort=3Drel&amp;type=3Dsimple&amp;published=3Don">ISO/IEC=20
  24754:2008</A> was published on 2008-08-15.&nbsp; It costs 96 CHF =
(about $100=20
  US) and is not (yet?) on the <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://standards.iso.org/ittf/PubliclyAvailableStandards/index.ht=
ml">list=20
  of publicly-available</A> (i.e., <A=20
  =
href=3D"http://blog.jonudell.net/2008/08/19/the-myth-of-free-standards/">=
free</A>)=20
  standards, last updated on 2008-08-08.</LI></UL>
