<H3>2008-08-18</H3><A name=3D4026013542762922595>&nbsp;</A>=20
<H2>Interoperable ODF: Finding Ground Truth</H2>
<DIV class=3DblogPost>
<DIV style=3D"CLEAR: both"></DIV>
<P></P>
<DIV=20
style=3D"PADDING-BOTTOM: 0px; MARGIN: 0px; PADDING-LEFT: 0px; =
PADDING-RIGHT: 0px; DISPLAY: inline; FLOAT: none; PADDING-TOP: 0px"=20
id=3Dscid:0767317B-992E-4b12-91E0-4F059A8CECA8:5f16cbf2-ff0b-4a92-bcac-a9=
d67d546842=20
class=3DwlWriterSmartContent>Technorati Tags: <A=20
href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/Jesper%20Lund%20Stocholm" =
rel=3Dtag>Jesper Lund=20
Stocholm</A>, <A href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/ODF" =
rel=3Dtag>ODF</A>, <A=20
href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/OpenDocument%20Format" =
rel=3Dtag>OpenDocument=20
Format</A>, <A =
href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/Microsoft%20Office%202007"=20
rel=3Dtag>Microsoft Office 2007</A>, <A=20
href=3D"http://technorati.com/tags/Document%20Interoperability%20Initiati=
ve"=20
rel=3Dtag>Document Interoperability Initiative</A></DIV>
<P></P>
<P>Jesper Lund Stocholm has found his files from the <A=20
href=3D"http://orcmid.com/blog/2008/08/microsoft-odf-interoperability-wor=
kshop.asp">Microsoft=20
Document Interoperability Initiative ODF Workshop</A>.&nbsp; His post, =
"<A=20
href=3D"http://idippedut.dk/post/2008/08/18/DII-ODF-workshop-the-good-stu=
ff.aspx">DII=20
ODF Workshop - the good stuff</A>", shares the nitty-gritty =
on-the-ground=20
experience of transferring ODF documents from OpenOffice.org to =
Microsoft's=20
pre-beta Office 2007 SP2 implementation and back again.&nbsp; There's a =
download=20
of eleven test files, each in two forms, along with PDFs of how they=20
render.&nbsp; There's an OpenOffice.org version of each document.&nbsp; =
Then=20
there's the Microsoft Office 2007 SP2 pre-beta ODF saving of the same=20
document.&nbsp; This is enough to discern how the the two applications =
handle=20
application-specific features from other applications and express=20
application-specific features of their own.</P>
<P>There are some great lessons becoming available with regard to =
interoperable=20
use of document formats.&nbsp; Here's what I see in terms of the =
Microsoft=20
Office and OpenOffice.org implementations of ODF:</P>
<UL>
  <LI><STRONG>Being standard is not the same as being=20
  interoperable.</STRONG>&nbsp; <BR>Lund Stocholm points out, "The =
result of the=20
  validation is that all files generated by Microsoft Office 2007 SP2 =
are valid=20
  ODF 1.1-files."&nbsp; The validation is essentially syntactical and =
that is=20
  not going to deal with all of the tolerated implementation =
variability,=20
  semantic bugs, and need for out-of-band agreements where the =
specification is=20
  (purposely and perhaps valuably) left =
wishy-washy.<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
  <LI><STRONG>There's a tremendous amount of binary information packaged =
in OO.o=20
  2.4 and Office 2007 ODF document implementations</STRONG>.<BR>This =
information=20
  is carried in outside-of-ODF namespaces and MIME types for which there =
is no=20
  mutual agreement.&nbsp; This can be reconciled among the different=20
  implementations, and we might expect more harmony before Office 2007 =
SP2=20
  ships, assuming there are no intellectual-property difficulties not =
covered by=20
  existing non-assertion covenants.&nbsp; This is a tricky area with=20
  socio-political and competition-law ramifications (illustrated by how =
no one=20
  seems to be bothered by the amount of binary material used in OO.o's=20
  implementation of ODF).<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp;=20
  <LI><STRONG>ODF-specification versioning is going to bother us for =
years, if=20
  not forever</STRONG>.<BR>Version churn is going to be a serious =
problem until=20
  those able to insist on demonstrable interoperability among =
applications=20
  compel some rational process for dealing with specification and =
implementation=20
  incompatibilities and defects,&nbsp; The stakes are now raised for =
achieving=20
  useful up- and down-level accommodation of specification and =
(deviating but=20
  widespread) implementation versions.&nbsp; Although I can see no way =
the ODF=20
  spreadsheet-formula problem could have been avoided, in particular, we =
must=20
  face two painful situations:=20
  <UL>
    <LI>XML namespaces for ODF are not dealt with as contracted =
interfaces with=20
    explicit discrimination of additions and changes between versions of =
the=20
    specifications.=20
    <LI>Requiring private agreement on spreadsheet formulas through at =
least ODF=20
    1.1 is going to force dealing with at least three versions in the =
future,=20
    something like<BR>- a Microsoft Excel formula namespace (better: an =
ECMA-376=20
    or IS 29500 one),<BR>&nbsp; <FONT size=3D2=20
face=3D"Courier New">xmlns:msoxl=3D"http<!-- stop URL recognition =
-->://<!-- -->schemas.microsoft.com/office/excel/formula"<BR></FONT>-=20
    an OpenOffice.org formula namespace,<BR>&nbsp; <FONT size=3D2=20
    face=3Dmonospace>xmlns:oooc=3D"http<!-- stop URL recognition =
-->://<!-- -->openoffice.org/2004/calc"<BR></FONT>-=20
    the default ODF OpenFormula namespace when finally introduced into =
ODF<BR>-=20
    versions of the above with their individual defects and incompatible =

    implementations<BR>&nbsp;&nbsp; </LI></UL>
  <LI><STRONG>It's the application [stupid?]<BR></STRONG>People don't =
deal with=20
  formats and the nuances of format versions, allowed options, and =
private=20
  agreements.&nbsp; People deal with software and the quality (and =
fidelity) of=20
  the electronic document that the software provides.&nbsp; Expecting =
individual=20
  users to be self-consciously attentive to limitations on conformance =
and=20
  interoperability is even more hopeless than demanding meticulous =
adherence to=20
  security policies and practices in ordinary office work.&nbsp; What =
people do=20
  want is for their interoperability case (however articulated) to just=20
  work.&nbsp; In reality, even "Save as ..." is asking too much.=20
  <UL>
    <LI>The first part of this lesson is going to involve recognition of =
the=20
    degree to which end-users are going to address interoperability by =
choosing=20
    specific software and believing interoperability is achieved, the=20
    ever-popular solution.=20
    <LI>The second part of this lesson is recognition of the distance =
between=20
    the current state and one with broader interoperability and =
confident=20
    substitution of alternative software choices.&nbsp; The differences =
among=20
    major ODF implementations will reveal how easy it is to lose=20
    interoperability while conforming to the current specifications.=20
    <LI>Ultimately, we may have to accept that we are unwilling to pay =
the price=20
    for significant interoperability assurance except under =
extraordinary=20
    circumstances.&nbsp; The "cost of interoperability" debate is ahead =
of=20
    us.</LI></UL></LI></UL>
<P>I don't foresee the <A =
href=3D"http://nfoworks.org/nfoWorks.htm">Harmony=20
Principles</A> alleviating this situation in any way.&nbsp; At best, I =
expect it=20
to help us appreciate the cost of interoperability and its improvement =
over=20
time.</P>
